I think I'm going to be destroyed on this question because I joined it so late and it took me so long to figure out what to do with the portoptimizer data. I do think bin 3 is most likely, although bin 2 shouldn't be ruled out, especially given that Oct 2021 was below Oct 2020.

Thanks @belikewater and @wackiewim for checking my numbers and sources. I revised my projections downward, but still wind up with a near coin toss for 1million based on the https://signal.portoptimizer.com numbers. That being said, those numbers are close, but usually higher than the source used to resolve the question https://www.portoflosangeles.org/business/statistics/container-statistics/historical-teu-statistics-2021. Furthermore, in 2021, imports have exceeded exports between 5-13%, so my estimate is 1million +/- 20k. May-21 21-Nov Import 540,803 505,164 (projected using 3 days from week 48 on https://signal.portoptimizer.com) Export 471,245 513,657 (est. 9% higher than imports) total 1,012,048 1,018,821

Wow, this is going to come down right at or below 1million based on numbers below. I took the record breaking month of May and compared it to reported import numbers for November thus far. The only unknown is the number of exports for November. Exports lag imports by an average of 9%, with a range of 6-13% in 2021. So even at the lowest rate of 6%, my projected total is 1,084,918. Close enough that it could slip below the 1million threshold, but almost certainly not below 900K.

It is looking more and more certain that the Port of Los Angeles will stay on track with the throughput levels achieved during the last couple of months and hit somewhere above 900,000 TEUs but less than 100,000 TEUs. Over all the port is experiencing a record year with a 22% increase in TUEs over 2020. (https://www.portoflosangeles.org/references/2021-news-releases/news_111821_octteu) Consistent with 2020, November is likely to be a little slower than October, but probably not by much given the national attention on continuing to get ships unloaded to ease pressure on the economy. Adjusting my forecast to 35% likely between 800,000 and 900,000 and 65% likely between 900,000 and 1,000,000 TEUs.

According to https://signal.portoptimizer.com, total imports for month of November will be ~524,000 which means the port would need a ~476,000 total exports to reach the 1 million mark. That would break the record set in May 2021. Of note, the extra day in May added ~15,000 to that record breaking month. All that being said, I can't find any current data on export volumes and will all of the attention on supply chains, inflation, etc. some government intervention could push the number a little higher and over the 1 million mark, so I can't discount that bin.

The real-time port data (signal.portoptimizer.com) seems to be pretty useless. It's not at all the same as the data used to resolve the question, and I'm coming to the conclusion that it can't even be trusted relative to previous years or months. Comparing Nov weekly data to last year's weekly data, Nov 2021 should come out below last year and in bin 2. Comparing the absolute number for Nov (projected 516k) to the absolute number for October (472k), Nov 2021 should be at 987k, in bin 3, close to bin 4. I would have been better off never to have looked at any of the port real-time data.
Bogged down by dwelling imports and empties, October cargo volumes through the Port of Los Angeles fall year-over-year despite long line up of ships waiting to offsload.

The portoptimizer.com numbers have been updated. The previous week's total and this week's forecast remain unchanged. There is large uncertainty, but the current numbers available through portoptimizer.com suggest that Nov 2021 total import TEUs will probably be just under Nov 2020 total import TEUs and that Nov 2021 total TEUs will likely be < Nov 2020 total TEUs, which would put the forecast in bin 2. (See my previous forecasts for details.) But, I realized that the same forecast method would have underestimated October's numbers. So, new forecast minimum for Nov: 0.985/0.98 * 1.925 * 466k = 902k. But even this is likely an underestimate by up to 60k, as I think the portoptimizer data, even used relative to the numbers they give for previous years, often underestimates current TEUs relative to previous years. So, I'm shifting my forecast up. I do think bins 1 and 4 are out at this point, but there's so much uncertainty with the port data that bin 2 is still quite possible.

As of Sat afternoon, the port has not updated numbers from Friday. The port's numbers for Nov imported TEUs are currently 514,061, or 98.5% of Nov 2020. (Again, these are not useful as absolute values but instead as approximate relative values.) That puts my best forecast for Nov at 0.985 * 1.925 * 466k = 884k. Their current numbers strongly predict bin 2, but I do expect their numbers for this week and next to change substantially over the coming week. Also, the current prediction is very close to the line between bins 2 and 3.

The port's numbers for the rest of the month have been revised slightly, so that their numbers for Nov imported TEUs are now 514,061, or 98.5% of Nov 2020. (Again, these are not useful as absolute values but instead as approximate relative values.) That puts my best forecast for Nov at 0.985 * 1.925 * 466k = 884k. On the one hand, their current numbers strongly predict bin 2. On the other hand, I do expect their numbers for this week and next to change substantially over the coming week, and the current prediction is very close to the line between bins 2 and 3.

It's Friday, and the week's imported TEUs in the Portoptimizer Signal data are still pretty high. They'll go through at least one more revision, perhaps ending up between 115k and 135k, but probably somewhere in the middle.

If the port gets through everything on their list for this week and next, then they'll just barely make it to bin 3. There is a real chance of bin 2 happening but not much chance of bin 4. There are only 6 more days of port work for this forecast.

The October 2021 number is out: 902,643.90 TEUs, down 7.96% from October 2020 (@DNK89 ). I had predicted that the the Oct 21 number would be "probably at ~94%-95% of Oct 2020 but possibly lower," so I wasn't too far off. So this gives me more confidence in predicting the November number based on using the 2021 Port Signal data relative to 2020 data in the same publication: https://signal.portoptimizer.com/ Also, note that October total exported TEUs were 92.6% of total imported TEUs, in line with September's 92%.

If the port data can be counted on to reveal approximate relative relationships in import TEUs vs. the same weeks last year, then even if the remaining couple weeks of Nov end up just a touch under last year's numbers, bin 2 will still be out because week 1 was so high. Lowering bin 2, and waiting for Oct numbers to come out. The next 2 weeks would need to be extraordinary to reach bin 4. I would go higher on bin 3 if I were more certain about the relationship between the numbers the port reports in real time and their monthly totals that are used to resolve this question.

I should allow for a greater possibility that the next 2 weeks could see much higher or lower TEUs than the same weeks last year, and also that the current port data might not track well, even in relative terms, with the question resolution data.

I think that with this week's TEUs potentially falling further below the same week's numbers in 2020, bin 4 is almost out of the question. And with last week's numbers, bin 1 is almost out of the question.

So far, this week looks like it's going to end up close to or below the same week last year. That makes bin 4 much less likely because of how much higher the second half of Nov would need to be compared to 2020.

I hesitate to rely on any aspect of the portoptimizer signal data, as they are so unreliable and inscrutable, but they do suggest that so far, Nov 2021 imported TEUs might be >12% greater than Nov 2020 imported TEUs.

If I give any credence to the data coming out of the Port of LA about current week TEU volumes vs. the same week in 2020, it appears that week 44 volumes were >10% above last year, which would push Nov into bin 4 if the trend is real and continues. I think I'm going to have a terrible score on this question because I started it near the end and am still figuring out how best to use any of the weekly port data, if at all. Anyone else looking at https://signal.portoptimizer.com/ or https://tower.portoptimizer.com?

The Port Signal data is claiming that they estimate Week 44's imported TEUs to be either 16.00% or 5.48% above the same week last year. (The data contradicts itself; see my previous forecasts for discussions of this.) If the week does end up somewhere between 5% and 16% above last year, then this makes the last 2 bins more likely. I don't know what to make of their data, though.

I think the real-time data coming out of the Port of LA is pretty useless. It's too all over the map. My best guess, from looking at the soup of data, is that October 2021 will come in below October 2020, probably at ~94%-95% of Oct 2020 but possibly lower. Because Oct 2020 was 27% above Oct 2019, a higher percentage than for any other month in 2020, and Nov 2020 was 22% higher than Nov 2019, I'll predict that all else equal, Nov 2021 will come in at 100% - (22/27)*5.8% = ~95% (+/-1%) of Nov 2020.

I just realized that the Signal report has different numbers from the other data at portoptimizer.com and from the data used to resolve the question. I have seen few worse data nightmares coming out of one organization. https://signal.portoptimizer.com/ https://tower.portoptimizer.com/dashboard/signal

Yesterday, I adjusted my forecast up a bit because the port forecast for this week was still so high, as of Wednesday. But it adjusted down again and is now only 1.78% higher than last year this week. I bet it will be adjusted even lower tomorrow and again after the week is over. The pattern is clear: 9 out of 11 of the past weeks have seen TEU volumes lower than last year. I had hoped that the current focus on the port might mean things would take off, but they do not seem to have the leadership and/or powers they need to clear the backlog. So I suspect that Nov 21 will be below Nov 20, or at most about 2% greater. And then the question is how low. Oct 21 is likely to be 82% of Oct 20. Oct 20 was 27% above Oct 19, and Nov 20 was 22% above Nov 19, so I suspect Nov 21 won't be as low as 82% of Nov 20. But it could easily be 90% of Nov 20, right on the lines between bins 1 and 2. I'll see how this week's TEUs come in and adjust from there. It's looking most likely that Nov 21 will be ~95% of Nov 20. Further info: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1350451
I should leave open the possibility that things will speed up.
Building on my earlier forecast. I think Nov 21 is likely to come in at about 90% of Nov 2020.

September 2021 showed a 2.3% increase in year-on-year container counts. A troubling sign is massive amount of unloaded containers and the sharp drop in containers exported.

Port of LA's revised forecast numbers as of 11/2: Week ending: forecast import TEUs Oct 31: 150091 * 6/7 Nov 7: 120955 Nov 14: 159220 Total 410k, much lower than yesterday's forecast of 516k for the same weeks. So it's clear that there's massive volatility in the port's forecasts. Revising downward accordingly.

November TEUs is likely to be at least somewhat higher than it was in 2020 given that for most of 2021 each month has seen higher TEU numbers than in 2020. However, that differential has been going down since the summer months. It seems likely that the majority of the merchandise arriving at the Port of Los Angeles intended for the holiday shopping season would have arrived by at least October, or early November at the latest. So, any "bump" due to anticipated holiday season merchandise would have already passed through the port in October. In November 2020, the Port of Los Angeles handled 889,748 TEUs (https://www.portoflosangeles.org/business/statistics/container-statistics/historical-teu-statistics-2020). Despite an average increase in TEUs overall for 2021 over 2020 of 26.5%, the July, August, and September average were only 1.84%. I forecast that the November number will be just over 900,000 TEUs, about a 1% increase.

Forecast for imported TEUs for the next 3 weeks from the Port of LA: https://twitter.com/PortofLA/status/1455195565080203265 For Oct 31 through Nov 20, the forecast is for a total of 430,061 TEUs to be imported. More details in the tweet above, where they link to a lot more details here: https://signal.portoptimizer.com/ Extrapolating to the last week and a half of Nov, and cutting off 1/2 week for the Thanksgiving holiday, I'd estimate that a reasonable current forecast for Nov imported TEUs would be ~573k. Obviously this could change if there's a big change in operations.

The average number of container ships waiting for a parking space at LA/LB (not at anchor, not at berth) is increasing. It doubled in October. It was 20 on Oct 1, and 42 yesterday. The backlog is increasing, even as the ports unload record numbers of containers. And apparently at least one shipper, Maersk, is now just passing the fines along to customers. So, I think it's unlikely that the fines are going to have much of an effect. So it's mostly back to considerations of number of container vessels at berth, average time at birth, number of working days each month, etc. And let's not forget Thanksgiving. Will the port be operational that weekend? And when will the port of LA move to 24/7 operation, if at all? LB is 24/7, but LA isn't.

I was driving along PCH a few weekends ago along the Malibu corridor, one can see a number of cargo ships upon the horizon waiting this far from the port. This is not normal any time of the year and although action is being taken to address the backlog it is doubtful that there will be a reduction before the end of the year.
Looking at the numbers again. Things would have to change a lot for bin 4 to happen. Hopefully, things will change a lot, but for now, I'm lowering my forecast for bin 4.
The fines might have a big impact.... Increasing weight on the last bin a bit.

November 2020 was 10% less than October 2020 (probably due to Veterans Day and ), so I'm estimating 819,000 units moved. My estimate ignores the White House announcement about '24 hour operation' because Port of LA only has one section working 24 hours (and even 24 hours is a misnomer because they're only squeezing in another 5 hours... inclusive of shift change time). As per this post by the CEO of Flexport, the port cranes aren't working at 100% capacity... likely because they have no where to put the containers. However, with 50,000+ independent truckers forced into bankruptcy by the lockdowns, I don't foresee enough truckers restarting operation within 5 weeks. Similarly, even if they call up 50,000 National Guardsmen who can drive trucks, where are they going to source the Mac truck cabs from? https://www.portoflosangeles.org/business/statistics/container-statistics/historical-teu-statistics-2020 https://www.zerohedge.com/markets/port-congestion-worse-leman-crash-flexport-ceo-warns

I think that it will be very close to 1M. 24-7 operations will increase capacity, but 30 days and Thanksgiving (I assume work will go through the holiday, but there will be some slowdown and likely less truck traffic clearing things out). September's numbers come to just over 30k TEU/day.
I honestly think this may come down to the fact that November is a 30 day month, falling just below the 1 million mark.

Based on monthly stats for 2021 and the statements from Port of Los Angeles Executive Director below, I estimate November totals will be VERY close to the 1 million mark, but not sure if will be above or below. Absent any disasters at the port, lower than 900k is a remote possibility.

Looks like port hours will be increasing, which warrants a significant shift in my forecasts toward more TEUs. "On Wednesday, the White House will announce that the Port of Los Angeles will remain open 24/7, moving to a schedule that the Port of Long Beach adopted three weeks ago. Together, those California ports have the worst backlog in the country, with 80 ships waiting to dock as of Tuesday night, according to the Marine Exchange of Southern California." https://www.politico.com/news/2021/10/13/supply-chain-christmas-crisis-515874

It's tempting to put more weight in bin 4 now that they are running 24 hour operations to deal with a backlog of cargo. However, there are logistical problems that make it hard to ramp up. The highest volume the port has ever reported is 1.012 million TEUs while the average rate over the last 5 years is 790,649. The recent rates above 900k are already historically high. I get the impression that the November number will be very close to 1 million TEUs, but it's not clear on which side the final tally will fall. Of course, there is also a risk that a bottleneck slows down the entire process.
Updating based on recent backlog & 24/7 news to model probabilities as roughly the same as YTD to cover the backlog aspect, and skewed about double towards the high end to account for the 24/7 side.

I haven't done much analysis on the potential impact yet, but the white house is getting involved and has announced 24/7 operations for the port to help clear the backlog. The port has only ever done more than a million TEUs once, so it's hard to lift it more than this without that further analysis. I'll update again probably soon.

outside view: Average for last 5 Novembers: 850,556. Average for Jan-Aug 2021: 909,132. May 2021 was 1,012,047. inside view: More cargo is sitting off the port than can possibly be unloaded in a month and more ships are coming. Some ships may be diverted, but not enough to pull LA below max capacity. The limiting factors (as I see them) are trucking capacity, rail capacity and crane capacity. Crane capacity is likely the all time high (over 1 mil), truck and rail are the real question. Right now I don't see a reason truck and rail capacity will be different in Nov than they have been in the last few months.
August numbers came in ~950k, shifting towards that gravity slightly.
